in article <1993apr27.172335.23392@magnus.acs.ohio-state.edu> bbarnard@magnus.acs.ohio-state.edu (bret d barnard) writes: >with spring upon us it's time to start waxing again. i was wondering if anyone >had any suggestions about waxes and polishes. i know carnuba wax is often >recommended on the net, but i was wondering about the colored waxes to cover up >some minor scratches. do the colored waxes give on overall good quality shine? >are they good for the paint or clear coat? > >what about liquid glass, is it a clear polish which dries clear; thus filling >scratches? is it good for the paint/clear coat? > >please post with both good and bad experiences. and hey, let's name names >(brands) here! ;^) all gimmicks! stick with plain 'ol carnauba wax that's non-abrasive. eagle 1, meguiars, turtle wax, and a few others are good examples. the colored waxes just color in the scratches so they're not so apparent. the better approach is to buff minor scratches completely off with a cleaner/mild abrasive. never tried liquid glass, although i still have this sample they sent me a few years back. aaron
